{"award_age":57.0,"bio_image":"full\/9464780bf92b6e63cbe527d422161a5fb60c2911.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"Germany","date_of_birth":"1853-09-16T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1927-07-05T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/e\/eb\/Albrecht_Kossel_nobel.jpg\/220px-Albrecht_Kossel_nobel.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albrecht_Kossel","mini_bio":"<p><b>Ludwig Karl Martin Leonhard Albrecht Kossel<\/b> (16 September 1853 \u2013 5 July 1927) was a German <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biochemist\" title=\"Biochemist\">biochemist<\/a> and pioneer in the study of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetics\" title=\"Genetics\">genetics<\/a>. He was awarded the Nobel Prize for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1910 for his work in determining the chemical composition of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nucleic_acid\" title=\"Nucleic acid\">nucleic acids<\/a>, the genetic substance of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cell_(biology)\" title=\"Cell (biology)\">biological cells<\/a>.<\/p><p>Kossel isolated and described the five <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Organic_compounds\" title=\"Organic compounds\" class=\"mw-redirect\">organic compounds<\/a> that are present in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nucleic_acid\" title=\"Nucleic acid\">nucleic acid<\/a>: <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Adenine\" title=\"Adenine\">adenine<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cytosine\" title=\"Cytosine\">cytosine<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Guanine\" title=\"Guanine\">guanine<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thymine\" title=\"Thymine\">thymine<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Uracil\" title=\"Uracil\">uracil<\/a>. These compounds were later shown to be <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nucleobases\" title=\"Nucleobases\" class=\"mw-redirect\">nucleobases<\/a>, and are key in the formation of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/DNA\" title=\"DNA\">DNA<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/RNA\" title=\"RNA\">RNA<\/a>, the genetic material found in all living cells.<\/p><p>Kossel was an important influence on and collaborator with other important researchers in biochemistry, including <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Henry_Drysdale_Dakin\" title=\"Henry Drysdale Dakin\">Henry Drysdale Dakin<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Miescher\" title=\"Friedrich Miescher\">Friedrich Miescher<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edwin_B._Hart\" title=\"Edwin B. Hart\">Edwin B. Hart<\/a>, and his professor and mentor, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Felix_Hoppe-Seyler\" title=\"Felix Hoppe-Seyler\">Felix Hoppe-Seyler<\/a>. Kossel was editor of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biological_Chemistry_(journal)\" title=\"Biological Chemistry (journal)\">Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Physiologische Chemie<\/a> (Journal of Physiological Chemistry) from 1895 until his death.<\/p><p>Kossel also conducted important research into the composition of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Protein\" title=\"Protein\">protein<\/a>, and his research predicted the discovery of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polypeptide\" title=\"Polypeptide\" class=\"mw-redirect\">polypeptide<\/a> nature of the protein molecule.<\/p><p>The <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albrecht_Kossel_Institute_for_Neuroregeneration\" title=\"Albrecht Kossel Institute for Neuroregeneration\">Albrecht Kossel Institute for Neuroregeneration<\/a> at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Rostock\" title=\"University of Rostock\">University of Rostock<\/a> is named in his honor.<\/p>","name":"Albrecht Kossel","place_of_birth":"Rostock","place_of_death":"Heidelberg ,  Germany","text":"Albrecht Kossel , Physiology or Medicine, 1910","year":1910.0}